As a student at the University of Manitoba in the Bachelor Social Work Program, I hope to see more of you here! ☺️ 

The University of Manitoba is the largest post-secondary university in the province with more than 100 undergraduate, master’s and doctoral programs. Most first-year students take University 1, a unique approach to entry-level studies that allows students to take courses required for their chosen program while providing exposure to several other disciplines. The University of Manitoba also offers direct entry into many other programs in faculties such as business, engineering and music. UM is home to more than 2,500 First Nations, Métis and Inuit students - more than 250 are graduate students. The university is home to one of the largest Indigenous student populations in Canada. International students make up 21.8% of the student population. UM’s Fort Garry campus sits alongside the winding Red River in south Winnipeg. The Rady Faculty of Health Sciences - which includes the colleges of medicine, dentistry, nursing, pharmacy and rehabilitation sciences! 

Learn more about UM: www.umanitoba.ca

John Holdren, Science Advisor to the President of The United States of eight years spoke at Arctic Encounter in Alaska and warned what new science is saying about climate change;

“Things are happening faster then we expected and more powerfully then we expected”. 

He spoke about permafrost in the Arctic by saying; “in terms of of rapid climate change on the region, we’ve learned that permafrost thaw is not only affecting and damaging buildings and roads and infrastructure. Accelerating costal erosion with severe threats to the viability of costal communities, all of this particularly acute for Indigenous communities. But In addition, it is also releasing viruses and toxic substances that have long been safely stored in frozen ground. This that is directing threatening human health in the region”.

My community of Inuvik and many other communities in the arctic of the world are located on permafrost. We are already seeing the affects of climate change and now the Arctic is warming three times greater than the global average. More  conversations need to happen and more actions need to be taken to stop climate change 🌎

It was such an awesome day at the Tuktoyaktuk vet clinic in NWT. I got to stop by to meet the vet team, including Dr. Michelle Tuma, tour the temporary clinic, and learn about VWB/VSF's work to increase access to vet care across Canada's North. Thank you so much for having me! 🐕

VWB/VSF's Northern Animal Health Initiative is dedicated to increasing veterinary access across northern Canada, with a focus on remote communities where vet visits are often a plane-ride away. By working on an invite-only basis, and closely with community liaisons in each community we visit, our goal is to enhance the health of animals, and by doing so, ensure that people living with or near them remain healthy, too. One way we do this is through vaccinations, like rabies, which ensure that pets are protected from dangerous diseases and don't spread them to humans. Beyond vaccinations, we also provide general vet checkups, spay/neuter surgeries, emergency care, and training sessions for community members interested in learning more about animal wellness. In our partner communities, we train lay vaccinators to administer vaccines when vets aren't accessible, and offer opportunities to learn pet first aid or other skills identified by community members. @vwb_vsf_canada

I’m so grateful for the opportunity to share my experience with hyperemesis gravidarum during pregnancy and having the opportunity to spread more awareness about something that gets so overlooked. The journey of pregnancy is so different for everyone, and in a lot of cases extremely difficult for so many reasons that unless you’ve experienced it, will never really be able to fully understand. After experiencing pregnancy I have nothing but respect for all the amazing women who have gone through the journey of bringing life into this world. 

@globalnews -Canadian fashion model Willow Allen, who is 34-weeks pregnant, has been suffering extreme nausea and vomiting throughout her pregnancy. 

In an interview with Global News Thursday, the Inuk model said she has ended up in hospital multiple times to get IV fluids for dehydration.

“I think it’s really hard to explain to people just how severe the sickness really is and how debilitating it really is,” Allen, who is from the Northwest Territories, said.

In the UK alone, between one to two hundred wanted pregnancies are terminated a year because of the severity of hyperemesis gravidarum

Allen, who was featured in Vogue last month, said she lost 15 pounds at the beginning of her pregnancy and she had to take a lot of nausea medication to keep things down while trying to gain back that weight.

“I’ve never been in such a weak physical state before and just having such little control over your life essentially because of how limited you are and not being able to do really anything for yourself when it’s that severe – it was really scary. ”

Our baby is due in 5 weeks and I can't believe that they are so close to being here. After what has been the hardest experience of my life with how sick I've been these last 8 months, I'm so grateful I was feeling well enough now to go on this last trip together as a family of two. This has felt like the perfect close to a chapter and our hearts are so ready for what is ahead ❤️

We’re having a boy!! 💙

I couldn’t be more excited to share this news. From the beginning of my pregnancy we thought we wouldn’t find out the gender until the baby arrived. I loved the idea of keeping it a surprise because that’s what our parents had done for us. But through this pregnancy it was so difficult at the beginning to think about pregnancy without thinking of how hard each day had been because of the sickness. We decided to find out the gender at 25 weeks and it brought us so much joy finding out we are having a little boy. Picturing him and what parenthood will look like has been the most exciting few months and we cannot wait to meet him
